  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does a vendor advocate actually do in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A vendor advocate works on the seller's side of a property sale. They interview agents on your behalf, recommend a shortlist, help you negotiate the agency agreement (Form 6 in Queensland), review the marketing plan, attend opens or auctions if you cannot, and act as a sounding board through the campaign. They do not sell the property themselves. Your appointed real estate agent still runs the marketing and the negotiation. The advocate is a layer of independent oversight between you and the agent."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does a vendor advocate cost in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The pricing structure that almost every Brisbane vendor advocate uses is a referral split, not a separate fee. The advocate takes a share of the appointed agent's commission, typically 20 to 35 percent of the agent's gross commission, paid by the agent. The vendor pays no direct fee to the advocate but pays the agent's normal commission. A small number of advocates charge a flat fee (commonly $5,000 to $15,000) or an hourly rate as an alternative model. The economics of the referral-split model are the most important thing to understand before you engage anyone calling themselves a vendor advocate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When is a vendor advocate genuinely worth it for a Brisbane seller?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Vendor advocacy genuinely helps in four situations. First, executors of a deceased estate where the executor is interstate, overseas, or unfamiliar with Brisbane property. Second, vendors going through divorce or separation who need a buffer between themselves and the listing decisions. Third, time-poor professionals who genuinely cannot dedicate the hours required to interview agents and run the campaign. Fourth, vendors with complex or premium properties where independent strategic input from someone who is not selling the property has real value. For the majority of owner-occupiers selling a standard inner-east home, the same outcome is achievable by interviewing three local agents directly and choosing the one with the strongest comparable evidence and the clearest plan."
      }
    }
  ]
};
